FBIS3-60091 "jptdd003__l94056" JPRS-TDD-94-003-L Document Type:JPRS Document Title:Narcotics 19 January 1994 AFRICA GHANA Businessman Receives Sentence of 24 Years for Cocaine Smuggling AB1701212694 Accra Ghana Broadcasting Corporation Radio Network in English 1300 GMT 14 Jan 94 AB1701212694 Accra Ghana Broadcasting Corporation Radio Network Language: English Article Type:BFN [Text] A Ghanaian-born businessman has been sentenced to 24 years in jail for his involvement in smuggling 160 million pounds worth of Colombian cocaine into Britain. (David Katcher), 42, of Manchester in northern England, was convicted last July at a New Castle court on two charges of importing cocaine and [words indistinct] weighing one and a half pounds. The sentence was delayed so that [words indistinct] and profits made from the clients seized. But the court was told (Katcher) received only 320,000 pounds out of which only 8,850 pounds was recorded. (Katcher), who runs textiles and building firms and was exporting construction machinery to Ghana, turned to cocaine smuggling because of huge debts. After the cocaine and the first shipment in October 1991 was distributed and sold, a tip-off to customs officers led to the second load being intercepted in a wave of arrests in Togo in 1992.
